The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Monday, March 22, 2004  LOOSE CHANGE
																								 The entry age for Kotak Preferred Term Plan has been reduced to 18 years. Until now, the scheme was available only to people over the age of 25 years. The policy is now available to everyone between 18 and 60 years. It is a pure risk policy, which covers lives at a nominal premium. The plan can be bought at a lower premium by people who meet the preferred lives criteria  for instance, people who do not smoke or consume tobacco in any other form. The Kotak Term Plan can also be used to cover outstanding debts like mortgages and home loans.																								 March 26 has been set as the record date for the declaration of dividend in three equity-linked savings schemes  Sundaram Tax Saver, Escorts Tax Plan and Birla Equity Plan. The rate of dividend for Sundaram is 60 per cent while Escorts has proposed a dividend rate of 80 per cent. Birla Mutual Fund has not indicated the dividend to be paid. Investments in these schemes up to Rs 10,000 are eligible for tax rebate under section 88.																								 Dividend is being announced in two equity funds this week. Franklin Templeton Mutual Fund has declared March 23 as the record date for dividend payment in Franklin India Prima Plus Fund, an open-ended equity fund. HSBC Mutual Fund has set March 24 as the record date for declaration dividend in HSBC Equity Fund.
